Does it matter if the US declares war on ISIS? In the wake of Thursday's deadly attack in Nice, France that left over 80 dead, Donald Trump advocated for a declaration of war against ISIS. When asked by Fox News' Bill O'Reilly whether he would ask Congress for a declaration of war against ISIS, Trump said "I would, I would. This is war." Asked later Thursday about Trump's response by CNN's Anderson Cooper, Clinton said it was "clear" that the U.S. was at war with terrorist groups, but she said it "was a very different kind of war." But, she did not address the issue of a formal declaration, arguing for greater intelligence gathering, rather that additional military force. "We're at war against radical jihadists who use Islam to recruit and radicalize others in order to pursue their evil agenda," Clinton added. But aren't we at war with ISIS already? The short answer is no. Article One, Section Eight of the U.S. Constitution says "Congress shall have the power...to declare War." The U.S has been conducting airstrikes against ISIS for years and has sent trainers and special operations forces to help combat the terror group. But the U.S. hasn't actually formally declared war since 1942, when Congress issued a voted to for a declaration of War against Nazi Germany's allies, Bulgaria, Hungary, and Romania. Modern U.S. conflicts have been governed by the War Powers Resolution of 1973. Passed in the wake of America's unpopular involvement in the Vietnam War, the act sought to limit the ability of the President to send U.S. troops into combat without Congress' approval. "In an absence of a declaration of war" the resolution requires Congressional notification and approval "whenever United States Armed Forces are introduced into hostilities" within 60 days of their deployments Recent military interventions in Afghanistan and Iraq were sanctioned by Authorizations for the Use of Military Force, or AUMFs, passed by Congress in 2001 and 2003 respectively. The administration and a large portion of Congress think current fight against ISIS is supported by the 2001 AUMF for the battle against the Taliban and al Qaeda because ISIS originated, in part, out of al Qaeda in Iraq. Isn't the President seeking a new authorization? Yes, in 2015 President Barack Obama asked Congress to formally authorize the use of military force against ISIS, however some Republicans in congress, while supportive of a new authorization, balked at his proposal because it put limits on the use of ground troops in the counter ISIS campaign. "I am prepared to support an Authorization for Use of Military Force that provides new legal authorities to go after ISIL and other terrorist groups. However, I will not support efforts that impose undue restrictions on the U.S. military and make it harder to win," Republican House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy said in 2015. It's not the first time Obama has clashed with Congress over such a resolution. During the 2011 intervention in Libya members of Congress such as Republican Sen. Rand Paul of Kentucky accused the administration of violating the War Powers Resolution by not obtaining congressional authorization. What are the consequences? U.S. Army Capt. Nathan Michael Smith sued the Obama administration in May over the lack of congressional approval for the war against ISIS. Smith, an intelligence officer stationed in Kuwait, said he backed the campaign but added he was seeking "to honor my oath" to the constitution. In response to the lawsuit, the administration's lawyers filed a motion to dismiss which said that because Congress has voted to provide funds to the anti-ISIS fight, Congress has in effect voiced their approval. "The President has determined that he has the authority to take military action against ISIL, and Congress has ratified that determination by appropriating billions of dollars in support of the military operation," the motion read. Does it make a difference? Potential Clinton VP Tim Kaine thinks so "I am deeply concerned about the legal basis for this war," Sen. Tim Kaine of Virginia told Secretary of Defense Ash Carter at a Senate Armed Services Committee in April. "The 2001 authorization does not provide a legal justification for this war," he said. Kaine who is rumored to be a leading candidate for Clinton's vice presidential nominee said that the absence of new Congressional action was undermining the fight against ISIS. "I don't think we've sent a message of political resolve as the political leadership, as the decision makers contemplated in Article One of the Constitution. We've not sent a message of resolve to our troops, we haven't sent them -- that message to our allies, we haven't sent that message to our adversaries," Kaine Said. If Kaine is picked as Clinton's running mate, it will be interesting to see if he and Trump stay on the same page on this issue. But with Clinton facing continued criticism from both Trump and her former primary opponent Sen. Bernie Sanders for her 2002 vote on authorizing the Iraq war it's possible some members of Congress will be in no rush to go on the record with a new vote.
